    "The narrative continues."
    # [Scene: Reworked Promenade | Evening — Same Day]

    scene bg ch15_182291_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The ocean huffs against engineered stone; a distant mechanized pump cycles; someone's radio crackles with logistics updates.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A low, insistent cello line guides the scene — steady pressure, not panic]
    "Maya Corvin descends the narrow path and feels the city's weight here like a physical thing: patched sealant, new anchor bolts, a line of sandbags that smell of old laundry. Market stalls hug the promenade now;"
    "sellers wheel carts stocked with rooftop lettuce and salt-tolerant herbs. Lio's murals turn over seasonally — faces and names she knows, surfacing like a ledger of memory. They are bright against the grit, and Maya finds"
    "her steps unconsciously set to the rhythm of that color."
    "A data buoy sponsor posts a live feed and the crowd gathers like weather: curious, worried, resigned. The tide has come higher than the models predicted. For a moment Maya watches, calculating in the way habit"
    "makes her: wave period, swell angle, the pressure on the softer sections. She has plans for all of it, but the plans are thin things against water."
    "Elias Kahn finds Maya near a collapsed stretch where community grafting has held but a temporary boardwalk has snapped. He is winded from travel — just back from a meeting across the bay — and there"
    "is that line at the corner of his eyes that Maya has learned reads municipal pressure."
    show elias_kahn at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kahn "They called me on the ferry. The storm front isn't over. How bad is it here?"
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "Patchable. But not with what's on hand. We'll need the pontoons and the volunteer rig team. Lio's kids are not going to stop painting for this."
    "Elias Kahn: (a breath) 'I'll pull what I can. I—' (he pauses) '—I have to keep the report clean. If it looks like the pilot failed, the funding dries.'"
    "Maya holds his gaze long enough for the city to make a noise between them both — a practical noise, made of ledger lines and human cost."

    maya_corvin "We already know the score. Don't let the ledger be the only story tonight."
    "Elias Kahn: (softly) 'You always give the ledger a heartbeat.'"
    "The exchange is small and layered. Maya doesn't need promises; she needs presence. He offers both, uneven as they are. It is enough for now."

    menu:
        "Organize the volunteer pontoons yourself":
            "Maya barks orders with the efficiency of someone used to moving neighbors into lines of work. It feels good and hollow at once — effective but exhausting."
        "Let Elias coordinate municipal support":
            "Maya steps back and lets Elias use his channels. The municipal trucks come slower, bureaucratically clean, but they arrive with equipment her hands alone couldn't lift. She wonders which ruin would have been worse."

    # --- merge ---
    "The narrative continues."
    # [Scene: Market Stalls | Night]
    hide elias_kahn
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch15_182291_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter threaded with the dull anxiety of a community used to counting losses; a child's recorder plays a tune that sounds like a ledger turning page by page.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, single-voice guitar — reflective, minor]
    "Maya walks between crates and conversations. Neighbors exchange updates in clipped sentences: which street pumps failed, who needs a generator, where a foundation heaved. The market keeps feeding the neighborhood and, in feeding it, keeps a"
    "story alive. Lio paints a new mural in the corner while humming. When he looks up, there is paint on his chin and relief in his smile."
    show lio_corvin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lio_corvin "They want to put a plaque where Mrs. Ortega's house used to be. Make it say 'Remembered by the people who stayed.'"
    "Maya Corvin: (pause) 'Make it say 'Remembered and kept.' The people who stayed also did the keeping.'"

    lio_corvin "That's too righteous."
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "Good. We'll make it messy then."
    "The joke softens the edge for a second. There are laughs, and then there is the return to the list of repairs and calls. Maya tucks her compass into her palm that has long since learned to hold both grief and options."
    # [Scene: Independent Board Hearing Room | Two Days Later]
    hide lio_corvin
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch15_182291_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Chairs scrape, a cough; a recorder hums. Outside, the city breathes: the distant slap of waves and the soft murmur of the market below.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse strings — restrained, unflinching]
    "Maya sits in the front row like someone who keeps the minutes in her bones. Board members rotate; Rafi sits with a stack of volunteer sign-ups. Camila 'Kai' Navarro hovers by the door, hair caught by"
    "a collar in the low wind, eyes narrowed but softer than the last time Maya faced her across a table. There is a history in her posture: efficiency learned into something that sometimes looks like listening."

    "Board Member" "We'll hear an update from the monitoring team. Then public comment."
    "Dr. Sima Raza's voice comes through with the steady reliability of someone who still believes data matters even when people are the subject."
    show dr_sima_raza at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_sima_raza "The hybrid sections have reduced peak inundation by thirty percent on average, but localized failure points remain at engineered-organic junctions. Maintenance cycles need scaling."
    "The room nods; some faces are hopeful, some resigned. Maya offers testimony. She speaks not as a single angry voice but as someone who has sewn governance out of neighborly vigilance."
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "We keep this living because living can flex. But living is labor. It needs funded time, not emergency funding after collapse. Our board is living proof: quarterly oversight, community representation, and a mandate to adjust actionables, not just write them."
    "A woman in the back raises her hand with the tremor of someone who has been made to move before."

    "Neighbor" "What about when investors push for a second concrete wall? How do we stop that?"
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro stands, for the first time in years speaking to this room with a voice that used to be polished for CEOs but now carries gravel."

    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro" "We don't stop pressure by denying it exists. We absorb it into design. The hybrid model is not an argument against scale; it's a way to make scale humane."
    "Her words land like a cold thing between Maya. They are useful and insufficient. The brittle hope in the room changes shape; everyone has learned the language of compromise but not all the appetite for its costs."
    "You: (This label appears in original draft but should be normalized; handled below.)"

    maya_corvin "Humane doesn't mean invisible costs. Decisions have human ruins."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro: (stiff) 'And inaction has more ruin.'"

    maya_corvin "Then we make action less ruinous. Fund maintenance now. Enshrine community seats. Make 'emergency' narrow so oversight can't be evaded."
    "Elias Kahn: (quietly) 'You and I have argued the same point in seventy forms. Make it workable and we'll sign.'"
    "Maya Corvin: (after a breath) 'Then make it enforceable, Elias. Make it so that the people whose gardens feed their kids have a say in how we define the exception.'"
    "Elias Kahn: (searching for words) 'I will. I will push for clarity.'"
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro: (after a beat) 'I'll consult. But don't expect me to soften every corner. Not everything can be preserved.'"

    maya_corvin "Then we'll preserve what we can and name the costs out loud."
    "The exchange extends: small concessions, big wounds. Maya feels the room's energy like a tide: it rises, crests over the same shoals, and recedes. The board votes on the maintenance clause. The language is tighter than"
    "it would have been before the amendment — a narrow path between efficiency and oversight. It is not perfect. Maya knows the next storm will teach new words."
    "Maya lives with the aftertaste of loss. Houses whose doorframes she measured as a child are now plaques; the promenade still leaks at the seams on certain high tides; some neighbors left. The city bought time"
    "with a price tag and a ledger of cultural erasures. That accounting sits in her chest like a stone that will not smooth."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Nursery | Dusk — Weeks Later]
    hide dr_sima_raza
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch15_182291_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low hum of conversation, a pump churning below; the gulls are a distant chorus.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano returns, colder now. A single, unresolved chord lingers.]
    "Maya stands at the nursery's edge, wind pulling loose a stray of braid. Elias appears beside her, coat folded into a travel bag slung over his shoulder. He smells faintly of engine oil and institutional coffee."
    "He does not need to announce where he's been; the schedule of a municipal planner is a pattern Maya knows by heart."
    show elias_kahn at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kahn "Traffic was brutal. They wanted me to sign a fast-track on an adjacent project."
    show maya_corvin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "Did you?"
    "Elias Kahn: (a slow exhale) 'No. I argued for review. It cost me time. It cost me allies.'"

    maya_corvin "It always does."
    "He turns to look at the shoreline where lights blink over the living breakwaters. A patch of the promenade has been re-tethered; volunteers laugh in the dark while they work, exhausted and fierce."

    elias_kahn "This is not how I pictured… ' (he searches) 'us. But it's a version I can stand behind."

    maya_corvin "Neither is it how I pictured it. I thought the plan would be purer. That we could keep everything we loved and repel everything that threatened it."
    "Elias Kahn: (half-smile) 'We'd be children to believe in purity. We are adults who still try.'"

    maya_corvin "That's an improvement."
    "The two of them stand with a distance that is measured and chosen, not accidental. Their partnership has its rhythms: bursts of closeness, periods of administrivia, arguments that end in compromise and sometimes in quiet loneliness."
    "It is not the all-consuming fire of manic romance. It is durable in the way habit is durable: by showing up."
    "Maya thinks of the cost — the houses, the murals that got painted over, the names that moved into plaques — and of what remains stubborn and alive: the market stalls, the nursery, the breath of"
    "the Low Row. She thinks of Lio's laughter and Rafi's hands, callused and precise. She thinks of Camila 'Kai' Navarro across the table: her eyes sometimes soft when she thinks no one watches. She thinks of"
    "Elias's steady exasperations and his small, infuriating kindnesses. The ledger of loss is long; so is the list of work to do. The life Maya committed to is not heroic so much as endless."
    hide elias_kahn
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch15_182291_7 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Radios chattering; the slapping of hurried footsteps; a buoy's alert tone — insistent but not panicked.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell to a moderate intensity — urgency without chaos]
    "The high tide that had been a caution becomes a test. Maya feels the arousal climb — not frantic, but focused. This is the labor she signed up for: to keep a precarious thing from breaking. She moves, because movement is less despairing than standing still."
    show maya_corvin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_corvin "Rafi, the northern tie needs the second anchor. Lio, cut the extra lines. Elias, call the tow for the pontoons. Camila—' (she doesn't finish; Camila 'Kai' Navarro is already there, hands steady) '—we need your drone to map the scour."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro: (without ceremony) 'Deploying. Watch the sharp edge by sector three.'"
    "The team folds into roles. There are short, clipped exchanges — commands softened by familiarity. The work is exacting: hands on ropes, boots on slick planks, voices calling out measures in half-sentences. Maya feels a fierce,"
    "exhausted solidarity — the practical solidarity of people who have learned to repair the city the way one patches a wound."
    "As the tide recedes, Maya tallies the damage with the measured dread of someone who knows how long healing takes. Some sections held. Some did not. A couple of houses will need new foundations; a small shrine washed clean. The living breakwaters will need re-grafting."
    "Maya presses the compass into her palm, feeling its scratch against skin that has known both triumph and small griefs. The brass is warm and cannot point the way. It is a relic and a charm, useless for navigation yet indispensable for memory."
    "Maya did not win the ideal. She did not lose everything. The shoreline she loves still alters her; the city still exacts payment. The amendment she fought for survives as a living, imperfect governance: quarterly hearings,"
    "appointed community seats, maintenance budgets that must be re-argued every cycle. The Low Row endures as a remade community, beautiful in its repairs and haunted by what had to be set aside."
    "Love has survived, but not unscarred. Maya's relationship with Elias is not the novel romance of grand gestures. It is work: check-ins in between meetings, letters scribbled on forms, nights spent hauling sandbags and mornings of"
    "quiet conversation over improperly brewed coffee. It is an arrangement of two people choosing, again and again, to keep working the seams."
    "Camila 'Kai' Navarro consults sometimes now, her manner both clinical and unexpectedly tender when a child asks about the sea. There is an uneasy respect between Maya — not reconciliation so much as a practical truce."
    "Rafi keeps teaching; his hands show where patience and insistence meet. Lio keeps painting, because if anything can be a rebellion against erasure, it's color."
    "Maya tucks the compass back beneath her jacket. The shoreline ahead will always demand attention: new designs, new politics, new storms. There will be further losses and further saves. There will be seasons when grief floods"
    "in and seasons where the nursery yields market profit and pride. The work, as it always was, is relentless. Maya used to imagine a single decisive victory. The city taught her a different truth: preservation is"
    "a practice, not a finish line."
    "Maya breathes the saline air and lets the ache sit where it wants. It is a heavy thing — not unendurable, but precise and insistent. She folds that ache into her daily rounds, into meetings, into"
    "grafts and hearings and late-night repairs. She keeps watch because keeping watch keeps things alive."
    hide maya_corvin

    scene bg ch15_182291_8 at full_bg
